# Navigation & Information Architecture

Navigation is the structure users use to find, reach, and move between content. Good IA is invisible — users find what they need without thinking about the system. Bad IA makes users feel lost.

## Information Architecture Principles

### Match user mental models
- Organize content the way users think about it, not the way the organization stores it
- OOUX provides a strong foundation: objects are natural mental models. Users think in terms of "Students," "Assessments," and "Classes" — not "Data Entities" or "Module 3"
- Test IA with card sorting (open sort to discover groupings, closed sort to validate existing structure)
- If >30% of users would look for something in a different location, the IA has a problem

### Objects as IA anchors
- In OOUX, objects are the primary navigation units. The Object Library is browsable by object, not by feature or workflow
- Object detail pages are hub pages — they link outward to related objects, creating a navigable web
- This fights the **Isolated Objects** anti-pattern: every object should be reachable from related objects, not just from a master list

### Progressive depth
- Use the **three page types** from OOUX: Landing pages (overview), List pages (browse/filter), Detail pages (deep content)
- Each click should feel like going deeper into the content, not sideways into confusion
- Breadcrumbs and back links help users understand depth and retrace their path

## Navigation Patterns

### Global navigation
- Present on every page in a consistent position (Caboodle: top nav bar)
- Contains 5–7 top-level items maximum — more requires grouping or mega-menus
- Active item is visually distinguished (`aria-current="page"`)
- Logo always links to the home page

### Local navigation (within a section)
- Use secondary tabs, sidebar nav, or in-page anchor links
- Secondary tabs work well for switching between views of the same object (Overview, Relationships, Reference)
- Sidebar nav works for long reference pages with many sections

### Breadcrumbs
- Show the user's path from the root: Home → Object Library → Student
- Use `<nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">` with an ordered list
- The current page is the last item, not linked, with `aria-current="page"`
- Essential for pages more than 2 levels deep

### Object-to-object navigation
- Relationship links on Object Guide pages (Student → Class, Student → Score) create a network users can traverse
- "Related objects" sections at the bottom of detail pages encourage exploration
- This is the OOUX principle: humans navigate most naturally through relationships between objects

## Wayfinding

Users need to answer three questions at all times:

1. **Where am I?** — Active nav tab, page heading, breadcrumbs, distinct visual treatment per section
2. **Where can I go?** — Visible navigation options, related content links, CTAs
3. **Where have I been?** — Visited link styles (`:visited`), breadcrumbs, browser back button support

### Wayfinding signals
- **Active states** on navigation items (highlighted tab, bold sidebar link)
- **Page titles** that match the nav label exactly — if the nav says "Object Library," the page heading says "Object Library"
- **Consistent layout** per section — all Object Guide pages share the same structure, so users learn the pattern once
- **URL structure** that mirrors the IA: `/objects/student` makes location obvious

## Continuity & Cross-Page Consistency

### Structural continuity
- Navigation position, footer content, and page shell remain identical across pages
- Users should never feel like they've left the site when navigating between sections
- Transition effects (if any) should be subtle and consistent

### Visual continuity
- Shared color palette, typography, and spacing across all pages
- Object identity colors persist from the library to the detail page to embedded mentions
- Card designs are consistent: an object card on the library page looks the same as an object card embedded in another guide

### Behavioral continuity
- Tabs work the same way everywhere (click to switch, keyboard arrow keys)
- Code blocks always have a copy button
- Interactive controls (dropdowns, toggles, filters) use the same component patterns
- Scroll position is preserved when returning via back button

### Content continuity
- Terminology is consistent: if you call it "Student" on one page, don't call it "Learner" on another (unless explicitly noting synonyms)
- Data consistency: if the Object Library card shows "42 attributes," the detail page should show 42 attributes
- Status labels, priority levels, and categorical terms use the same vocabulary site-wide

## Search (Future)

When implementing search:
- Place the search input in a consistent, prominent position (Caboodle: top nav, `⌘K` shortcut)
- Show results grouped by type (Objects, Resources, Glossary Terms) with clear type labels
- Support type-ahead / autocomplete for known entities
- Include recent searches and suggested queries
- Show the number of results
- Provide empty-state guidance when no results are found ("No results for 'Asignment'. Did you mean 'Assignment'?")

## Link Design

- Links should be visually distinct from non-linked text (underline + color is the strongest signal)
- Link text should describe the destination: "View the Student Object Guide" not "Click here"
- External links should indicate they open in a new context (icon or text like "opens in a new tab")
- Visited link color should differ from unvisited — it helps users track where they've been
- Skip links ("Skip to main content") should be the first focusable element for keyboard users

## URL Design

- URLs are part of the UI — they should be readable, predictable, and stable
- Use lowercase, hyphenated slugs: `/objects/proficiency-prediction` not `/Objects/ProficiencyPrediction`
- Avoid query parameters for primary navigation (they're bookmarkable but hard to read)
- Never break existing URLs — if a page moves, redirect the old URL
